        "id": 1072905
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-03T08:36:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is documented as:\n\n```\n *   \u003cli\u003eFailures during acknowledgement may surface as runtime exceptions.\n```\n\nI think forcing a checked exception tends to push clients into boilerplate try/catch that either logs-and-swallows or wraps into runtime anyway.\nProcessing will happen in `accept()`, which does not expose a checked exception in its signature (also, the `acking` might happen in separate threads and lambdas), so I think unchecked exceptions are a better fit here.",
      "parentUuid": "fed6cf7d_79e9afce",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 47,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 47,
        "endChar": 13
      },
      "revId": "09e90357eeeea77c15600a6d5d40dac7df01dc3c",
      "serverId": "173816e5-2b9a-37c3-8a2e-48639d4f1153"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "31721c61_4e696ef4",
        "filename": "src/main/java/com/gerritforge/gerrit/eventbroker/MessageContext.java",
        "patchSetId": 14
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1072905
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-03T08:36:00Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e received messages are acked automatically or not.\n\nI think you are suggesting this as a way to understand whether auto-committing is enabled, as an alternative to the `noop()` strategy? I am not sure this would be the right approach: `ack()` is an operation that you **might** perform on a message, so I think its rightful place is the `MessageContext`.\n`isAutoAck()` would expose a committing strategy, which is at a higher-level and is not a property of a `message`.",
      "parentUuid": "a0205b47_4d6bc19b",
      "revId": "09e90357eeeea77c15600a6d5d40dac7df01dc3c",
      "serverId": "173816e5-2b9a-37c3-8a2e-48639d4f1153"
    },
